com.camerontec.catalys.core.session

Class ProcessingCompletionManager

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.camerontec.catalys.core.session.ProcessingCompletionManager
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    IProcessingCompletionManager

    public class ProcessingCompletionManager
extends Object
implements IProcessingCompletionManager
    Default IProcessingCompletionManager implementation.

    In a multithreaded message processing environment, processing of messages may not be completed in the order that messages were received. For example, messages 1 and 2 are received. Thread A gets message 1 and starts processing it. Thread B gets message 2 and starts processing it. For some reason, thread B finishes first and calls the Session's processedMessage method. Suppose we persisted message 2's message sequence number and then crashed. When we started up again FIX would assume that all messages prior to message 2 had been successfully received and processed, so would only request resending of messages after 2. However, if processing of message 1 did not complete, this would not be correct. We should request a resend from message 1. Message 2 will be received again but the application should be able to handle messages that are sent twice (Fix provides a PossDup flag for exactly this reason).

    The job of this class is to manage these out of sequence processed messages. In the above example, when message 2 reports that it has been processed it would be recognized that we still haven't heard from message 1 and message 2 would be stored in a holding area. When message 1 reports that it has been processed, message 2's message sequence number will be persisted.

    Implementation Note:
    The store of out of sequence processed messages is NOT persisted. They are stored in memory. Persisting them is unnecessary.
    If we crash, the knowledge that these messages have been processed will be lost. This means that they will all be re-requested when FIX restarts. Since any FIX application must be able to handle duplicate messages, this should not be a problem.

    See ThreadedProcessingClient for a working example of multi-threaded message processing.

    This class assumes there is exactly one thread adding messages for processing. There may be multiple threads processing messages. Consistency is only guaranteed under these conditions.

      If more than this number of messages are waiting to be processed (at the time of an addMessage(IFIXMessage)) we throttle the producer in order to allow the processor(s) some time to catch up.

      The producer throttle timeout in milliseconds.
